WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:16.020
&gt;&gt; Sharon Horowitz:
Hi, good afternoon.

00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:19.080
Welcome to the African and
Middle Eastern Reading Room.

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:21.750
On behalf of the
Geography and Map Division

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:23.600
and the Hebraic Section,
let me thank you

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:26.200
for coming to today's program.

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:27.660
My name is Sharon Horowitz.

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:30.580
I'm a reference librarian
in the Hebraic section.

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:34.970
The Hebraic section began, or
considers itself to have begun

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:37.030
in 1912 with the receipt

00:00:37.030 --> 00:00:39.280
of 10,000 Hebrew
books and pamphlets.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:42.230
Whose purchase was
made possible by a gift

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:44.920
from New York philanthropist
Jacob Schiff.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.960
From those humble beginnings,
our collections have grown

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:50.130
to about 250,000 items.

00:00:50.130 --> 00:00:54.000
In Hebrew, Yiddish,
Ladino, Judeo-Persian,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.440
and other Hebraic
script languages.

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:58.980
The Hebraic section also
includes an important collection

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:02.690
of books in Geez, Amharic,
and Tigrinya, the languages

00:01:02.690 --> 00:01:05.360
of Ethiopia, past and present.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:08.000
Our section's holdings
are particularly strong

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.690
in the subject areas of
Bible, Rabbinics, Liturgy,

00:01:11.690 --> 00:01:15.440
Hebrew Language and Literature,
Responsa, and Jewish History.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:17.700
Two of our missions
in this division are

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:19.060
to publicize our collection

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:21.200
and to bring people
into the Library.

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:27.150
One way we accomplish this
is by holding lectures

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:30.300
and having programs such as the
one we are hosting here today.

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:33.180
And now, a word about
our speaker.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:37.260
Professor Marcin
Wodzinski is a Professor

00:01:37.260 --> 00:01:38.640
of Jewish History
and Literature.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:40.480
And the Head of the
Department of Jewish Studies

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.970
at the University
of Wroc?aw, Poland.

00:01:42.970 --> 00:01:45.430
The scope of his
academic interests range

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:48.790
from the social history of
Jews in the 19th Century.

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:51.420
To the history of
the Jews of Silesia.

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:53.970
Jewish material culture,
and especially the history

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.940
of Hasidism and Haskalah.

00:01:56.940 --> 00:02:00.290
His publications include more
than 100 articles in English,

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:02.640
Polish, Hebrew, French,
and Czech.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:05.720
He has written an co-authored
and edited many books.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:08.920
And we are very honored to
have him speaking to us today

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:10.440
about his newest book.

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.420
The Historical Atlas
of Hasidism.

00:02:13.420 --> 00:02:16.690
Professor Wodzinski's
interest in Jewish history

00:02:16.690 --> 00:02:20.600
and culture began with
Jewish cemeteries.

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:22.670
He learned Hebrew so that
he could read the Jewish

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:25.610
and Hebrew inscriptions
on tombstones.

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:29.740
And he became fascinated by the
custom of Hasidic pilgrimages

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:32.660
to the graves of Hasidic rebbes.

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:37.220
His interest is not in the
writing of the great leaders.

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:41.610
But namely about the rank
and file of average Hasidim.

00:02:41.610 --> 00:02:45.390
And how they understood the
teachings of their leaders.

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:48.750
Two items of business
before we begin.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:51.290
Professor Wodzinski's
book is available

00:02:51.290 --> 00:02:53.800
for sale after the program.

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:58.620
And he has graciously agreed
to sign for anyone who'd like.

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.550
And also Michael
Klein of the Geography

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:04.440
and Map Division has prepared
a small display of interesting

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:07.490
and relevant maps related
to today's program.

00:03:07.490 --> 00:03:08.790
And they're on display

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:12.120
in our division's
conference room behind me.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:15.130
So please join us there
after the lecture.

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:19.040
This event is being videotaped
for subsequent broadcasting.

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:20.340
There'll be a formal question

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:22.910
and answer period
after the lecture.

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:25.570
At which the audience
is encouraged

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:27.330
to ask questions
and offer comments.

00:03:27.330 --> 00:03:32.050
But please be advised that your
voice and image may be recorded

00:03:32.050 --> 00:03:34.980
and later broadcast
as part of this event.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:37.980
By participating in the
question and answer period,

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:41.380
you are consenting to the
Library's possible reproduction

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:42.960
